'''Nancy O'Dell''' (born '''Nancy Evelyn Humphries'''; February 25, 1966)<ref>{{IMDb name|nm0640669|Nancy O'Dell}}</ref> is an American [[television]] host and entertainment [[journalist]]. She is co-anchor of the syndicated entertainment news show ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'', having joined the show on January 3, 2011. In May 2013, she received an Honorary Doctorate of Humanities from [[Clemson University]].

==Early life==
O'Dell was born in [[Sumter, South Carolina]], and moved to [[Myrtle Beach, South Carolina|Myrtle Beach]] as an infant. She has one sister. After her 1984 graduation from the now defunct Coastal Academy High School, she graduated with a ''[[summa cum laude]]'' bachelor's degree in marketing from [[Clemson University]] in 1990. At Clemson, O'Dell joined [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]]. She won the [[Miss South Carolina]] pageant in 1987, and represented the state at [[Miss America 1988]], where she won a preliminary swimsuit award. In 1990, in the [[Miss South Carolina USA]] pageant, she finished 1st runner-up to [[Gina Tolleson]], who became the 1st runner up in [[Miss USA 1990]] before winning [[Miss World 1990|Miss World]] that year.

==Career==
O'Dell began her broadcasting career as a reporter and anchor at [[WPDE]]-TV in her home town of Myrtle Beach, South Carolina. She later worked as morning news anchor and crime reporter at [[WCBD]]-TV in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. While there, her reports on the lenient police approach to DUI cases led to a State Law Enforcement Division investigation that resulted in authorities issuing more stringent directive for such cases. She was honored by the Associated Press with the Best Report of the Year Award (all media, South Carolina). In 1993, she joined NBC's [[WTVJ]] in Miami, co-anchoring the 5:30 pm news with [[Jackie Nespral]]. O'Dell left that station in 1995 to move to Las Vegas with her first husband.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} While there she worked as an entertainment reporter for the nationally syndicated tabloid show ''[[A Current Affair (U.S. TV series)|A Current Affair]]'' until the show ended in 1996.

===''Access Hollywood'' (1996–2009) ===
O'Dell joined the entertainment news program ''[[Access Hollywood]]'' when the program debuted in 1996.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/tv/nancy-o-dell-leaves-access-hollywood/|title=Nancy O Dell Leaves Access Hollywood|last=Wihlborg|first=Ulrica|date=December 17, 2009|work=|newspaper=PEOPLE.com|language=en-US|access-date=October 13, 2016|via=}}</ref> In addition to her work as ''Access Hollywood''<nowiki/>'s lead anchor, O'Dell contributed to NBC News's ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' and ''[[Dateline NBC]]''. She has covered such ceremonies as The Oscars, The Emmys, The Grammys, and The Golden Globe Awards, as well as co-hosting a number of pre-shows/arrivals for The Emmys and [[the Golden Globes]].

O'Dell co-hosted the [[Miss USA]] and [[Miss Universe]] competitions in 2004 and 2005. She co-hosted the New York City [[St. Patrick's Day]] Parade on WNBC from 2004 to 2006. She co-hosted the Miss USA 2006 pageant with [[Drew Lachey]], the Miss Universe 2006 pageant with [[Carlos Ponce]], and the Miss USA 2007 pageant with [[Tim Vincent]].

O'Dell appeared in minor roles in the television series ''[[Charmed]]'' ([[Deja Vu All Over Again (Charmed)|season 1 finale]] and [[A Witch's Tail (Part 2)|season 5 premiere]]). She also portrayed herself in ''[[Scream 2]]'' (1997), ''[[Scream 3]]'' (2000), and ''[[Scream 4]]'' (2011), and served as host and consulting producer of the [[USA Network]] talent competition ''[[Nashville Star]]'' for its first two seasons.

On January 13, 2008, after the [[65th Golden Globe Awards|65th Annual Golden Globe Awards]] were canceled as a result of the [[2007–08 Writers Guild of America strike]], she co-hosted NBC's ''65th Annual Golden Globe Awards Winners Special'' with ''Access Hollywood'' co-anchor Billy Bush.

In 2009, O'Dell hosted NBC's pre-show for the 66th Annual [[Golden Globes]] with [[Tiki Barber]] and [[Brooke Burke-Charvet|Brooke Burke]]. She portrayed herself in the ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' season three episode "Cheat It". She also appeared on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[Brothers (2009 TV series)|Brothers]]'', and in the same year she and [[Maria Menounos]] guest co-hosted ''[[WWE Raw]]'' on October 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/articles/11092738/11919858 |title=Fights, camera, Access! |publisher=World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE) |accessdate=September 5, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091009062953/http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/articles/11092738/11919858 |archivedate=October 9, 2009 }}</ref> O'Dell was to participate in the eighth season of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', paired with professional dancer [[Tony Dovolani]], but had to withdraw before the season started after injuring her knee during training; her replacement was [[Melissa Rycroft]].<ref>[http://tvwatch.people.com/2009/03/05/jewel-and-nancy-odell-withdraw-from-dancing "Jewel and Nancy O'Dell Withdraw from Dancing"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306230959/http://tvwatch.people.com/2009/03/05/jewel-and-nancy-odell-withdraw-from-dancing |date=March 6, 2009 }}</ref> O'Dell underwent [[arthroscopic surgery]] to repair a torn [[Meniscus (anatomy)|meniscus]] in her knee on March 20, 2009.<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20267593,00.html "Nancy O'Dell Recovering from knee Surgery"] ''People Magazine'', March 24, 2009.</ref>

O'Dell's departure from ''Access Hollywood'' was announced in December 2009. She left the show with two years left on her contract.<ref name=":2" />

On June 22, 2010, O'Dell hosted the ''Nashville Rising'' concert to provide flood relief for [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] residents, after [[2010 Tennessee floods|the floods in May of that year]]. She shared hosting duties with [[Tim McGraw]] and [[Faith Hill]].

===''Entertainment Tonight'' (2011–present) ===
On January 3, 2011, O'Dell joined ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' as a special correspondent, and she succeeded [[Mary Hart]] as co-anchor after Hart left the show in May 2011. An avid scrapbooker, in 2010 O'Dell partnered with Creative Memories<ref>{{cite web|title=Creative Memories Partner Nancy O’Dell Gives Away Scrapbooking Products on Rachael Ray Show|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2011/5/prweb8395504.htm|publisher=PRWeb.com|accessdate=March 6, 2012}}{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> to release her first collection of scrapbooking supplies, the Hummingbird Collection, and her second book, ''Full of Love: Mom-to-mom Advice for Enriching Families with Simple Photo Albums and Scrapbooking''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nancy O'Dell Partnership |url=http://www.creativememories.com/Content/NancyODell/NancyODell_Main.aspx |publisher=Creative Memories |accessdate=March 7, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309174505/http://www.creativememories.com/Content/nancyodell/nancyodell_main.aspx |archivedate=March 9, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>

==Personal life==
O'Dell was married to Dr. Richard O'Dell from September 30, 1995, to November 4, 2004. In 2005, she married Keith Zubchevich, and she is stepmother to his two sons, Tyler and Carson. O'Dell gave birth to their daughter, Ashby Grace, in 2007, at [[Cedars-Sinai Medical Center]] in Los Angeles.<ref>Ingrassia, Lisa. [http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20041876,00.html "Access Hollywood's Nancy O'Dell Has a Girl"], ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', June 11, 2007</ref> She said unexpected and surprising changes happened to her body during the pregnancy that prompted her to write a parenting book, ''Full of Life''.<ref>[http://www.cookiemag.com/entertainment/2009/03/nancy-odell Celebrity-Parent Profile: Nancy O'Dell @ Cookiemag.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090329092825/http://www.cookiemag.com/entertainment/2009/03/nancy-odell |date=March 29, 2009 }}</ref> She is the [[Muscular Dystrophy Association]]'s National [[Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis|ALS]] Ambassador.{{Citation needed|date=May 2015}} In September 2016, O'Dell filed for legal separation from Zubchevich.<ref>[http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/nancy-odell-separated-from-husband-of-more-than-10-years-w444884 Nancy O'Dell Separated From Husband of More Than 10 Years]</ref> In November 2017, the couple filed for divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/nancy-odells-estranged-husband-keith-zubchevich-files-for-divorce-one-year-after-separation/|title=Nancy O’Dell’s Estranged Husband Keith Zubchevich Files for Divorce One Year After Separation|last=Hautman|first=Nicholas|work=[[Us Weekly]]|date=November 22, 2017|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/nancy-o-dell-husband-reportedly-files-divorce-article-1.3651780|title=Nancy O’Dell’s husband reportedly files for divorce|last=Feldman|first=Kate|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=November 22, 2017|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>

In May 2013, O'Dell received an Honorary Doctorate of Humanities from [[Clemson University]]. At the ceremony, she spoke to the rest of the graduates, encouraging them to never give up in pursuing their dreams: "I decided that I would rather fail doing something I enjoyed than be successful doing something that would just be a grind [....] my wish for all of you is that you will do the same. Be who you are because you'll always be right."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clemson.edu/media-relations/4899/clemson-university-awards-3053-degrees-honors-alumna-nancy-odell/|title=Clemson University awards 3,053 degrees; honors alumna Nancy O’Dell|publisher=}}</ref>

